-- Japan, China, Malaysia, Philippines, Taiwan: Asian Bond, Currency Preview
-- Anil Varma
-- 2010-06-21T22:22:17Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-21/japan-china-malaysia-philippines-taiwan-asian-bond-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.21 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest inter-dealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 91.03 per dollar at 7:05 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The finance ministry plans to sell 28 billion yuan
($4.1 billion) of 10-year bonds tomorrow.  
 The yuan yesterday rose the most since a July 2005
revaluation and forwards jumped after China’s central bank ended
a two-year peg before a Group of 20 summit this week.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due May 2020 was 3.39
percent, according to the National Interbank Funding center. The
yuan was at 6.7976 per dollar.  
 India: The government will auction 30 billion rupees ($656
million) of treasury bills tomorrow. The yield on the 7.80
percent bond due May 2020 was 7.57 percent. The rupee was at
45.7525.  
 Indonesia: The government plans to sell one-year bills as
well as bonds maturing in seven and 15 years today.  
 The yield on the 11 percent bond due November 2020 was 8.05
percent, according to the Inter Dealer Market Association. The
rupiah was at 9,008 per dollar.  
 Malaysia: The central bank will report its foreign-exchange
reserves as of June 15. The reserves were $95.5 billion on May
31. The yield on the 4.378 percent note due November 2019 was
4.06 percent. The ringgit was at 3.1885.  
 Philippines: The finance department is scheduled to report
last month’s budget balance. The budget deficit was 131.6
billion pesos ($2.9 billion) in the first four months of the
year.  
 The yield on the 7.75 percent debt due February 2020 was
7.996 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange Corp.
The peso was at 45.458 per dollar.  
 South Korea: The government plans to raise as much as 340
billion won ($290 million) by selling 10-year inflation-linked
bonds on June 24.  
 The yield on South Korea’s 4.5 percent bond due in March
2015 was 4.49 percent. The won was at 1,171.95.  
 Taiwan: The seasonally adjusted jobless rate fell to 5.33
percent in May from 5.43 percent in April, according to a
Bloomberg survey before the statistics bureau releases the data
today.  
 The yield on the 1.375 percent bond maturing in March 2020
was 1.46 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The
Taiwan dollar was at NT$31.999.  
 Thailand: The central bank will today sell 18 billion baht
($558 million) of 28-day bills, 15 billion baht of 91-day bills
and 12 billion baht of 182-day bills.  
 The yield on the 3.875 percent bond maturing in June 2019
was 3.19 percent. The baht was at 32.28.  
